## 🎨 Quick Styling Correction for your Navbar Items

You mentioned wanting an item styled as `margin-left: auto` to be on the utmost right of the navbar.

Using **Flexbox** makes aligning items like this exceptionally clean. Here is how your `Navbar.tsx` JSX structure should look to support this:

```tsx
// Navbar.tsx
export default function Navbar({ onAddTaskClick, sortDirection, onSortChange }: NavbarProps) {
  return (
    <nav style={{ 
      display: 'flex', 
      alignItems: 'center', 
      width: '100%',
      padding: '15px 20px', 
      backgroundColor: '#282c34', 
      boxSizing: 'border-box'
    }}>
      {/* 1. Left item (Branding) */}
      <h1 style={{ margin: 0, color: 'white', fontSize: '20px' }}>📋 Workspace Board</h1>

      {/* 2. Right items container (pushes itself and everything inside to the far right) */}
      <div style={{ 
        marginLeft: 'auto', // 👈 Pushes this entire block to the right edge
        display: 'flex', 
        alignItems: 'center', 
        gap: '15px' 
      }}>
        <label style={{ color: 'white', fontSize: '14px', display: 'flex', alignItems: 'center', gap: '5px' }}>
          Sort by Date:
          <select value={sortDirection} onChange={(e) => onSortChange(e.target.value as any)}>
            <option value="asc">Earliest First</option>
            <option value="desc">Latest First</option>
          </select>
        </label>

        <button onClick={onAddTaskClick}>+ Add Task</button>
      </div>
    </nav>
  );
}

```

### Why this Flexbox approach is great:

Instead of putting `margin-left: auto` on a single button, putting it on a **wrapper container** that houses both your *sorting dropdown* and *add task button* ensures that your entire functional control suite is grouped together and pushed cleanly to the far right, while your branding stays firmly on the left!
